question:
If $a,b,c$ are positive integers less than $13$ such that \begin{align*}
2ab+bc+ca&\equiv 0\pmod{13}\\
ab+2bc+ca&\equiv 6abc\pmod{13}\\
ab+bc+2ca&\equiv 8abc\pmod {13}
\end{align*}then determine the remainder when $a+b+c$ is divided by $13$.

agents_response:
Add up all the equations to get $4(ab+bc+ca) \equiv 14abc \pmod{13}$, which simplifies to $ab+bc+ca \equiv a+bc \pmod{13}$.

Subtract this from each of the original equations in turn to get
\begin{align*}
ab\equiv b+ca\pmod{13}\\
bc\equiv a + c \pmod{13}\\
ac\equiv a + b \pmod{13}
\end{align*}

Subtracting $a$ for the first equation and $b$ for the third, then comparing, gives $c \equiv ab \pmod{13}$. Plug this to second equation to get $b \equiv a \pmod{13}$, and then into the third equation gives $a \equiv b \pmod{13}$. This gives $a \equiv b \equiv c \pmod{13}$. For least positive $a+b+c$, the remainder is $\boxed{3}$.
